  <subsection>
    <title>Omskakeling van een basis na 'n ander</title>
    <p>
      Veronderstel nou dat ons die basisse <m>\basis{B}</m> en <m>\basis{C}</m> ken, asook die koördinaatvektor <m>[\ve{w}]_\basis{B}</m> van <m>\ve{w}</m> in die basis <m>\basis{B}</m>,
     <me>
        [\ve{w}]_\basis{B} = \begin{bmatrix} -3 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}
      </me>,
      dit is, <m>\ve{w} = -3 \ve{b}_1 + 2 \ve{b}_2</m>.
      Hoe kan ons <m>[\ve{w}]_\basis{C}</m>,
      die koördinaatvektor van <m>\ve{w}</m> in die basis <m>\basis{C}</m> bereken?
    </p>

    <p>
      Die beste benadering is om elke vektor in <m>\basis{B}</m> as 'n lineêre
      kombinasie van die basisvektore in <m>\basis{C}</m> uit te druk.
      In die volgende figuur word die vektore <m>\ve{b}_1</m> en <m>\ve{b}_2</m> uitgebeeld teen die
      agtergrond van heeltallige lineêre kombinasies van die basis <m>\basis{C}</m>:
    </p>

      <image>
        <latex-image>
          <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
          \draw[blue, dotted] (-6, 3) -- (0, -3);
          \draw[blue, dotted] (-5, 3) -- (1, -3);
          \draw[blue, dotted] (-4, 3) -- (2, -3);
          \draw[blue, dotted] (-3, 3) -- (3, -3);
          \draw[blue, dotted] (-2, 3) -- (4, -3);
          \draw[blue, dotted] (-1, 3) -- (5, -3);
          \draw[blue, dotted] (-0, 3) -- (6, -3);

          \draw[blue, dotted] (-6, 3) -- (0, 3);
          \draw[blue, dotted] (-5, 2) -- (1, 2);
          \draw[blue, dotted] (-4, 1) -- (2, 1);
          \draw[blue, dotted] (-3, 0) -- (3, 0);
          \draw[blue, dotted] (-2, -1) -- (4, -1);
          \draw[blue, dotted] (-1, -2) -- (5, -2);
          \draw[blue, dotted] (0, -3) -- (6, -3);

          \draw[very thick, secondaryColor, ->] (0,0) -- node[pos=1.6] {\(\ve{c}_2\)} (1,0);
          \draw[very thick, secondaryColor, ->] (0,0) -- node[pos=1.6] {\(\ve{c}_1\)} (-1,1);
          \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0,0) -- node[pos=1.3] {\(\ve{b}_1\)} (2,1);
          \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0,0) -- node[pos=1.3] {\(\ve{b}_2\)} (1,2);\end{tikzpicture}]]>
        </latex-image>
      </image>

    <p>
      Ons lees af dat:
       <mdn>
        <mrow xml:id="b_in_terms_of_c">\ve{b}_1 \amp = \ve{c}_1 + 3 \ve{c}_2</mrow>
        <mrow xml:id="b_in_terms_of_c_2">\ve{b}_2 \amp = 2 \ve{c}_1 + 3 \ve{c}_2</mrow>
      </mdn>
    </p>

    <p>
      Daarom bereken ons:
      <md>
        <mrow>\ve{w} \amp = -3 \ve{b}_1 + 2 \ve{b}_2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = -3 (\ve{c}_1 + 3 \ve{c}_2) + 2(2 \ve{c}_1 + 3 \ve{c}_2)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \ve{c}_1 - 3 \ve{c}_2</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      Hiervan lees ons af dat
      <men xml:id="w_in_basis_C">
        [\ve{w}]_\basis{C} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix}
      </men>
      wat die korrekte antwoord is, soos ons weet uit <xref ref="correct_exp_w" />.
    </p>

    <p>
      Hierdie berekening kan in terme van matrikse uitgedruk word.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-change-of-basis-matrix">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Laat <m>\basis{B} = \left\{ \ve{b}_1, \ldots, \ve{b}_n \right\}</m> en
          <m>\basis{C} = \left\{ \ve{c}_1, \ldots, \ve{c}_n \right\}</m>
          basisse vir 'n vektorruimte <m>V</m> wees.
          Die <term>basisomskakelingsmatriks van
          <m>\basis{B}</m> na <m>\basis{C}</m></term> is die
          <m>n \times n</m>-matriks <m>P_{\basis{C} \leftarrow \basis{B}}</m> waarvan die kolomme die koördinaatvektore
          <m>[\ve{b}_1]_\basis{C}, \ldots, [\ve{b}_n]_\basis{C}</m> is:
          <me>
            \mat{P}_{\basis{C} \leftarrow \basis{B}} := \begin{bmatrix} \left[\begin{array}{c} \, \\ \ve{b}_1 \\ \, \end{array}\right]_\basis{C} \amp \left[\begin{array}{c} \,\\ \ve{b}_2 \\ \, \end{array}\right]_\basis{C} \amp \ldots \amp \left[\begin{array}{c} \, \\ \ve{b}_n \\ \,\end{array}\right]_\basis{C}  \end{bmatrix}\,
          </me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In ons deurlopende voorbeeld, sien ons uit
          <xref ref="b_in_terms_of_c" /> en <xref ref="b_in_terms_of_c_2" /> dat
          <me>
            [\ve{b}_1]_\basis{C} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}, \quad [\ve{b}_2]_\basis{C} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} \,
          </me>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Daarom is die basisomskakelingsmatriks van
          <m>\basis{B}</m> na <m>\basis{C}</m>
           <me>
            \mat{P}_{\basis{C} \leftarrow \basis{B}} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 3  \end{bmatrix}
          </me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      Voordat ons verder gaan, moet ons 'n aspek van matriksvermenigvuldiging hersien.
      Veronderstel ons groepeer <m>m</m> kolomvektore saam om 'n matriks te vorm:
      <me>
        \begin{bmatrix} \left[\begin{array}{c} \, \\ \text{C}_1 \\ \, \end{array}\right] \amp \left[\begin{array}{c} \,\\ \text{C}_2 \\ \, \end{array}\right] \amp \ldots \amp \left[\begin{array}{c} \, \\ \text{C}_m \\ \,\end{array}\right]  \end{bmatrix}
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      (Ons basisomskakelingsmatriks <m>\mat{P}_{\basis{C} \leftarrow \basis{B}}</m> is
      so gevorm.) Dan kan ons die produk van hierdie matriks met 'n kolomvektor soos volg bereken:
      <men xml:id="column_vector_multiplication">
        \begin{bmatrix} \left[\begin{array}{c} \, \\ \text{C}_1 \\ \, \end{array}\right] \amp \left[\begin{array}{c} \,\\ \text{C}_2 \\ \, \end{array}\right] \amp \ldots \amp \left[\begin{array}{c} \, \\ \text{C}_m \\ \,\end{array}\right]  \end{bmatrix}
      </men>
    </p>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Bewys die bostaande formule!
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Ons bevestig dat die <m>i^\text{ste}</m> inskrywing van die linkerkant van <xref ref="column_vector_multiplication"/> korrek is,  deur die definisie van matriksvermenigvuldiging te gebruik:
          <me>
            (\text{LHS})_i = (\text C_1)_ia_1 + \ldots + (\text C_n)_ia_n = (\text{RHS})_i
          </me>
          en ons is klaar!
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <p>
      Ons kan nou die volgende stelling bewys.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="change-of-basis-thm">
      <title>Basisomskakeling</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Veronderstel dat <m>\basis{B} = \left\{ \ve{b}_1, \ldots, \ve{b}_n\right\}</m> en
          <m>\basis{C} = \left\{ \ve{c}_1, \ldots, \ve{c}_n \right\}</m> basisse vir 'n vektorruimte <m>V</m> is, en laat
          <m>\mat{P}_{\basis{C} \leftarrow \basis{B}}</m> die
          basiskomskakelingsmatriks van <m>\basis{B}</m> na <m>\basis{C}</m> wees.
          Dan geld vir alle vektore <m>\ve{v}</m> in <m>V</m> dat
          <men xml:id="change-of-basis-in-action">
            [\ve{v}]_\basis{C} = \mat{P}_{\basis{C} \leftarrow \basis{B}} [\ve{v}]_\basis{B}
          </men>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Laat <m>\ve{v} \in V</m>.
          Brei <m>\ve{v}</m> in die basis <m>\basis{B}</m> uit:
          <me>
            \ve{v} = a_1 \ve{b}_1 + a_2 \ve{b}_2 + \cdots + a_n \ve{b}_n,  \text{i.e. }  [\ve{v}]_\basis{B} = \begin{bmatrix} a_1 \\ \vdots \\ a_n \end{bmatrix}
          </me>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Dan,
          <md>
            <mrow>[\ve{v}]_\basis{C} \amp = [a_1 \ve{b}_1 + \cdots + a_n \ve{b}_n]_\basis{C}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = a_1 [\ve{b}_1]_\basis{C} + \cdots + a_n [\ve{b}_n]_\basis{C}  \amp \amp  (<xref ref="lin_of_coord_vectors">Lemma</xref>)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =   \begin{bmatrix} \left[\begin{array}{c} \, \\ \ve{b}_1 \\ \, \end{array}\right] \amp \left[\begin{array}{c} \,\\ \ve{b}_2 \\ \, \end{array}\right] \amp \ldots \amp \left[\begin{array}{c} \, \\ \ve{b}_n \\ \,\end{array}\right]  \end{bmatrix}\left[\begin{array}{c} a_1 \\ \vdots \\ a_n \end{array}\right] \amp \amp <xref ref = "column_vector_multiplication"/></mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =    \mat{P}_{\basis{C} \leftarrow \basis{B}} [\ve{v}]_\basis{B} \, </mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In ons deurlopende voorbeeld, sê die stelling dat vir
          <em>enige</em> vektor <m>\ve{v} \in \mathbb{R}^2</m>,
          <me>
            [\ve{v}]_\basis{C} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp  2 \\ 3 \amp  3  \end{bmatrix} [\ve{v}]_\basis{B}  .
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          Dit geld in besonder ook vir ons vektor <m>\ve{w}</m>,
          waarvan die koördinate in die basis <m>\ve{B}</m> is:
          <me>
            [\ve{w}]_\basis{B} = \begin{bmatrix} -3 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}
          </me>.
        </p>

        <p>
          So in hierdie geval sê die stelling dat
           <me>
            [\ve{w}]_{\basis{C}} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp  2 \\ 3 \amp  3 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} -3 \\ 2\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix}
          </me>
          wat met ons vorige berekening <xref ref="w_in_basis_C" /> ooreenstem!
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <exercises>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Hierdie is 'n voortsetting van <xref ref="matrix_basis_exercise">Oefening</xref>.
          Beskou die volgende twee basisse vir <m>\Mat_{2,2}</m>:
          <me>
            \basis B = \left\{
            \text{B}_1 =   \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp  0 \\ 0 \amp  1 \end{bmatrix}, \,
            \text{B}_2 =   \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp  0\\ 0 \amp  -1 \end{bmatrix}, \,
            \text{B}_3 =   \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp  1 \\ 1 \amp  1 \end{bmatrix}, \,
            \text{B}_4 =   \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp  1 \\ -1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
            \right\}
          </me>

          <me>
            \basis C = \left\{
            \text{C}_1 =   \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp  1 \\ 0 \amp  0  \end{bmatrix}, \,
            \text{C}_2 =   \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp  -1 \\ 0 \amp  0 \end{bmatrix}, \,
            \text{C}_3 =   \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp  0 \\ 1 \amp  1 \end{bmatrix}, \,
            \text{C}_4 =   \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp  0 \\ 1 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}
            \right\}
          </me>

          <ol label="(a)">
            <li>
              <p>
                Bereken die basisomskakelingsmatrikse
                <m>\mat{P}_{\basis{C} \leftarrow \basis{B}}</m> en <m>\mat{P}_{\basis{B} \leftarrow \basis{C}}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Bereken <m>[\mat{A}]_\basis{B}</m> en <m>[\mat{A}]_\basis{C}</m>, waar
                <me>
                  A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Bevestig dat <m>[\mat{A}]_\basis{C} = \mat{P}_{\basis{C} \leftarrow \basis{B}} [\mat{A}]_\basis{B}</m> en dat
                <m>[\mat{A}]_\basis{B} = \mat{P}_{\basis{B} \leftarrow \basis{C}} [\mat{A}]_\basis{C}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Vir elkeen van die volgende word twee basisse <m>\basis{B}</m> en <m>\basis{B}'</m> gegee.
        Bereken die basisomskakelingsmatriks <m>\mat{P}_{\basis{B'}\leftarrow \basis{B}}</m>.
      <ol label="(a)">
        <li>
          <m>V = \Row_2</m>, <m>\basis{B} = ((1,3),(3,8))</m> en <m>\basis{B}' = ((2,-1), (-3,2)) </m>;
        </li>
        <li>
          <m>V = \Row_2</m>, <m>\basis{B} = ((2,-1), (-3,2)) </m> en <m>\basis{B}' =  ((1,3),(3,8))</m>;
        </li>
        <li>
          <m>V = \Poly_2</m>, <m>\basis{B} = (x, 2x^2-x+3, x^2+2x+2)</m>  en <m>\basis{B}' = (1+5x^2,x^2,3-x-2x^2) </m>.
        </li>
      </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Bereken die basisomskakelingmatriks
          <m>\mat{P}_{\basis{B} \leftarrow \basis{S}}</m> van die standaardbasis
          <me>
            \basis{S} = \left\{ 1, \cos x, \sin x, \cos 2x, \sin 2x \right\}
          </me>
          van <m>\Trig_2</m> na die basis
          <me>
            \basis{B} = \left\{ 1, \cos x, \sin x, \cos^2 x, \sin x\cos x \right\} \,
          </me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <xref ref="w_in_b_basis_exc"/> wys vir ons 'n basis <m>\basis{B} = \bopen \ve{b}_1, \ve{b}_2 \bclose</m> vir <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>, 'n agtergrond van heeltallige lineêre kombinasies van <m>\ve{b}_1</m> en <m>\ve{b}_2</m>, asook 'n ander vektor <m>\ve{w} \in \mathbb{R}^2</m>. Soortgelyk wys <xref ref="w_in_c_basis_exc"/> 'n ander basis <m>\basis{C} = \bopen \ve{c}_1, \ve{c}_2 \bclose</m> vir <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>, 'n agtergrond van heeltallige lineêre kombinasies van <m>\ve{c}_1</m> en <m>\ve{c}_2</m>, en dieselfde vektor <m>\ve{w} \in \mathbb{R}^2</m>.
      </p>
      <sidebyside>
        <figure xml:id="w_in_b_basis_exc">
          <caption>
            Die vektor <m>\ve{w}</m> teen 'n agtergrond van heeltallige lineêre kombinasies van die basisvektore van <m>\basis{B}</m>.
          </caption>
          <image>
            <latex-image>
              <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
              \draw[primaryColor, dotted] (-3, -9) -- (9, -3);
